<p>(b) On a day where it <alert>is raining</alert>, I claim that "today it is raining if and only if I am not telling the truth".
<br/>Which of the following options describes the truth of this statement.</p>

<p/><ol marker="(1)">
<li>This statement is true</li>
<li>This statement is false</li>
<li>This statement is neither true nor false since each option gives a contradiction</li>
<li>This statement could be either true or false</li>
</ol> 
<p/></div></statement>
<solution><div><h3>Worked solution:</h3>

<p>(a) The correct truth table for the implication operator is the following,</p>

<tabular style="border: 1px solid black; border-collapse: collapse; text-align: center; margin-left: 30px;">
  <row>
    <cell style="width:100px; border: 1px solid black"><m>A</m></cell>
    <cell style="width:100px; border: 1px solid black"><m>B</m></cell>
    <cell style="width:200px; border: 1px solid black"><m>A {\iff} B</m></cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell style="border: 1px solid black">true</cell>
    <cell style="border: 1px solid black">true</cell>
    <cell style="border: 1px solid black"><alert>true</alert></cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell style="border: 1px solid black">true</cell>
    <cell style="border: 1px solid black">false</cell>
    <cell style="border: 1px solid black"><alert>false</alert></cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell style="border: 1px solid black">false</cell>
    <cell style="border: 1px solid black">true</cell>
    <cell style="border: 1px solid black"><alert>false</alert></cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell style="border: 1px solid black">false</cell>
    <cell style="border: 1px solid black">false</cell>
    <cell style="border: 1px solid black"><alert>true</alert></cell>
  </row>
</tabular>

<br/>

<p>(b) To evaluate the given statement, we can separate the two claims as,</p>
<p style="margin-left: 30px">
  <m>A</m>: "it is raining"
  <br/><m>B</m>: "I am not telling the truth"
</p>
<p>We can now use the truth table in part (a) to evaluate the full statement.</p>

<br/>

<p>We know immediately from the information in the question that statement <m>A</m> is <alert>true</alert>, so we have a case of either the first or second row in the table.</p>

<tabular style="border: 1px solid black; border-collapse: collapse; text-align: center; margin-left: 30px;">
  <row>
    <cell style="width:100px; border: 1px solid black"><m>A</m></cell>
    <cell style="width:100px; border: 1px solid black"><m>B</m></cell>
    <cell style="width:200px; border: 1px solid black"><m>A {\iff} B</m></cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell style="border: 1px solid black">true</cell>
    <cell style="border: 1px solid black">true</cell>
    <cell style="border: 1px solid black"><alert>true</alert></cell>
  </row>
  <row>
    <cell style="border: 1px solid black">true</cell>
    <cell style="border: 1px solid black">false</cell>
    <cell style="border: 1px solid black"><alert>false</alert></cell>
  </row>
</tabular>

<br/>

<p>Then, from the table we see that the <alert>as long as there is not a contradiction</alert>, the statement could be either true or false.</p><p>Let us suppose first that the statement is <alert>true</alert>, so we are in the first row of the shortened truth table above. Since I am therefore telling the truth, we know statement <m>B</m> is <alert>false</alert>.<br/>Now looking at the relevant row in the shortened truth table, this <alert>does not</alert> correspond to the evaluation of <m>B</m>, so we have a contradiction and the statement <alert>cannot be true</alert>.</p><p>Let us suppose now that the statement is <alert>false</alert>, so we are in the second row of the shortened truth table above. Since I am therefore not telling the truth, we know statement <m>B</m> is <alert>true</alert>.<br/>Now looking at the relevant row in the shortened truth table, this <alert>does not</alert> correspond to the evaluation of <m>B</m>, so we have a contradiction and the statement <alert>cannot be false</alert>.</p><p>Then, considering both cases, the statement is <alert>neither true nor false</alert> since each option gives a contradiction.</p></div></solution>
<answer><p>true</p></answer>
<answer><p>false</p></answer>
